Tip

For the R chunks that take a significant time to run, e.g. ones containing cv.tree(), and randomForests(), you can set the R chunk option cache = TRUE. When you run a code chunk with cache = TRUE for the first time, the code is executed, and the results are stored in a cache directory associated with your R Markdown document. On subsequent runs, if the code chunk and its inputs (e.g., code, data, parameters) have not changed since the last run, the cached result is used instead of re-executing the code. Try to avoid having any library() calls in these cached chunks! For this reason, let’s load them all now:

Decision Trees

Exercise 3 (Decision Tree) (2 points) Use the rpart() function to train a decision tree on the training set to predict the salary using all available predictors. Plot your resulting tree1 and interpret the first three decision nodes.

library(rpart)

set.seed(42)

# Train a decision tree regressor
tree_model <- rpart(salary ~ ., data = train_data, method = "anova")

plot(tree_model,  margin = 0.1)
text(tree_model)

Exercise 4 (Test Error) (1 point) Evaluate the performance on the tree by calculating the test RMSE.

RMSE vs MSE

We will be comparing the Root Mean Square Error (RMSE) for this assignment. RMSE is expressed in the same units as the target variable, making it easier to understand the magnitude of prediction errors. In contrast, Mean Squared Error (MSE) is on a squared scale, which can result in larger numerical values that are less intuitive to interpret.

# Make predictions on test data
predictions <- predict(tree_model, newdata = test_data)

# Evaluate performance
rt_rmse <- sqrt(mean((test_data$salary - predictions)^2))
format(rt_rmse)
[1] "135550.2"

Random Forests

Exercise 5 (Train a random forest) (2 points) Use the randomForest() function to fit a random forest model with 500 trees on
the training data set. Set importance = TRUE since you will need to assess importance
of predictors later. You may use the default mtry (which is 𝑝/3 rounded down for
regression). Use a seed of random seed equal to your student number for reproducibility.

# see for reproducibility
set.seed(311+2024) # the seed should be their student number times 2

# fit the random forest
rf <- randomForest(salary~., importance= TRUE, data = train_data)

Exercise 6 (RF Test Error) (2 points) Calculate the test error of the random forest model on the test set. Compare this estimate with the OOB estimate.

# Predictions on the test set using the initial randomForest model

X_test <- test_data[,-2]
Y_test <- test_data$salary
  
predictions_rf <- predict(rf, newdata = X_test)

# Calculate MSE
(rmse_rf <- sqrt(mean((predictions_rf - Y_test)^2)))
[1] 112640.9

The last element of the $mse vector is the OOB estimate for error

# OOB Mean Squared Error
(rmse_oob_rf <- sqrt(rf$mse[length(rf$mse)]))
[1] 133346.5

The test RMSE for the RF model was calculated to be $112,640.9. The OOB error produced by the model was $133,346.5. The values are pretty similar.

Exercise 8 (Train the Bagging model) (2 points) Use the randomForest()function to perform bagging with 500 trees on the training data set. Be sure to set importance = TRUE since you will need to assess importance of predictors later. Use your student number times 2 for a seed for reproducibility.

To perform bagging we need to set mtry equal to the number of avaiable parameters, which in this case is 6 (=ncol(train_data) - 1 )

set.seed(2024) # the seed should be their student number times 2
bagg <- randomForest(salary~., importance= TRUE, data = train_data, mtry = 6)

Regularization

Feature scaling

In lecture we talked about the importance of scaling the numerical vectors before performing regularization. Note that for our data set, the only numeric predictors (years of experience and years at company) are on the same units. Therefore I do not feel the need to scale.

Exercise 11 (Design Matrix) (1 point) Use the model.matrix() function to create a matrix of predictor variables, converting categorical variables into dummy variables. By default, this function will include a column of 1’s for the intercept term. It’s essential to exclude this since glmnet adds it by default. You can achieve this using this by simply deleting the first column of 1’s returned by model.matrix().

model.matrix(y ∼ ., data)[, -1]
# Create the design matrix using model.matrix()
